<H1>IV. Multimedia Content Indication</H1>
<H3>
<U>Content Indication:</U> the process of explicitly presenting some part of the content for its better comprehension by the user.
<BR>
<UL>
<LI>Requirements<BR>
<a href="c7fig/7-5.jpg">fig. 7-5</a>: Interfacing multimedia contents.<BR>
<UL>
Human's Observation Modes:
<UL>
<LI>Glancing</LI>
<LI>Grazing</LI>
<LI>Browsing</LI>
<LI>Watching</LI>
</UL>
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>Smooth Stage Transition
<br>-transition should correspond to the continuous human thinking process
</LI>
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>Sense of Overview
<br>-cover a wide range of the related contents
</LI>
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>Sense of Positioning
</LI>
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>Effective Representation
<br>-not easy when content has temporal material
</LI>
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>Responsiveness
</LI>
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>Attractiveness
</LI>
</UL>

</LI>

<BR>
<LI>Content Indication Basics
<BR>-description of multimedia content should be separated into the content and attribute information
<BR>-The <U>core part</U> contains the actual media information.
<BR>-The <U>attribute information part</U> can contain coding information, content structure information, content profile information.
<BR>
<UL>
<LI>Indication Granularity</LI>
<UL>
<LI>Poster</LI>
<LI>Browser</LI>
<LI>Viewer</LI>
<LI>Magnifier</LI>
</UL>

</H3>
</BODY>
